title: Jhula - Manish Khushalani (2024)
description: The music video for "Jhula" by Manish Khushalani, released in 2024, explores themes of vulnerability, trust, and the delicate nature of relationships. The video combines Indian classical elements with contemporary electronic music, creating a unique visual and auditory experience. The narrative is driven by a series of intimate and evocative scenes that reflect the song's emotional depth, showcasing a blend of traditional and modern aesthetics that highlight the fusion of cultural influences. The visuals are crafted to complement the haunting melody and poignant lyrics, making for a captivating and immersive experience.

title: Her Morning Elegance (2009)
description: A collaborative stop motion film by musician Oren Lavie and Israeli photographer Eyal Landesman. The only stop-motion video to ever earn a grammy nomination, this whimsical video accompanies the song of same name by Lavie. The camera remains stationary while bedroom linens and clothing move across the mattress as personifications of the birds, trains, and fish she dreams of.
director: Oren Lavie, Yuval and Merav Nathan

title: "The Fear Cycle" Film - Unveiling Sleep Paralysis Through Art (2024)
description: "The Fear Cycle" film explores Nicolas Bruno’s experiences with Sleep Paralysis, a sleep disorder that causes vivid nightmares. Bruno transforms his fears into artwork, giving viewers a glimpse into each dream sequence. This film delves into Bruno's creative journey, showcasing his artistic process, dream journal entries, and theatrical renditions of his visions.

title: Ken Carson - Fighting My Demons (2023)
description: The music video for "Fighting My Demons" by Ken Carson, directed by Cole Bennett, was released in 2023 and features unique, glitchy visuals. The video presents a series of grainy, 3D footage that gives off the impression of being shot with night-vision goggles, offering a surreal viewing experience. It mainly showcases Ken Carson partying and performing his lyrics, creating a montage that aligns with the song's themes. The video's eerie and dark aesthetics were noted for drawing inspiration from the style of 1990s Japanese cinema, culminating in a profound, existential moment where Ken faces a haunting black void, adding depth and narrative to the visual experience.
